FAQ

tspan.tspan: The router cut too much in the negative direction, near the lower left corner of the
table.

text.tspan: You probably forgot to uncheck "Use offset" in V-Carve, so V-Carve assumed your origin
was at the center of your design.

tspan.tspan: Why is VCarve cutting outside of some curves but inside others?

text.tspan: You need to join your curves into one closed vector.

tspan.tspan: Start the VCarve software.
Open your DXF file by navigating to File > Open and selecting your file. You can export a
DXF from Onshape or other CAD program.
You might see a warning that says something about "CTABLESTYLE." Nobody knows what
this means; just click okay.
Uncheck "use offset."
Create an Easel account and project:
Go to https://easel.inventables.com, create an account or log in, and start a new project.
Import your G-code file into the new project by clicking Import G-code.
When asked about adding a "G-code header," click "I understand," even though that may well
be a lie.
Securely clamp down your material
Use the machine controls to jog the bit to the correct starting position above your
material.
Jog the bit down (Z-axis) until it just touches the surface of your material
Double-check that the material is secure and the bit is correctly positioned.
Click Carve to start the carving process.
Watch the machine while its carving. If something goes wrong, hit the big red emergency stop
button and turn off the spindle.
Once the carve is complete, turn off the spindle and unclamp and remove your part

text.tspan: Use the mouse to select all vectors in your design
Join open vectors.
Navigate to the tool paths tab.
With all vectors selected, choose the appropriate tool path operation for your
project. You should cut holes first, then pockets, then profiles.
Adjust depth per pass and cutting speed. With a 0.25 inch bit, you probably shouldn't
go deeper than 0.075 inches/pass or faster than 45 inches/min. You can finetune the
speed in Easel.
Click "Calculate" to generate the tool path based on your settings which will also
show a preview.
Save the toolpath as a G-code file to downloads The file extension should be .nc
